===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|sh|sla-pro|*a||and, but}}, from {{etyl|ine-bsl-pro|sh}} {{m|ine-bsl-pro|*ō}}.

====Conjunction====
{{sh-conjunction|c|a}}

# [[but]], [[and]] (compare {{m|sh|sc=Cyrl|а̏ли}})
#: {{usex|учио сам ц(иј)ело посл(иј)еподне, а ништа нисам научио|t=I studied for the whole afternoon, but I didn't learn anything|lang=sh|inline=1}}
#: {{usex|а како бисте ви то направили?|t=and how would you do that?|lang=sh|inline=1}}
# [[while]] (on the contrary), [[whereas]]
#: {{usex|столови су црвени, а столице су зелене|t=the tables are red, whereas the chairs are green|lang=sh|inline=1}}
# {{context|with {{term|sc=Cyrl|да|lang=sh}} {{term|sc=Cyrl|не|lang=sh}}|lang=sh}} [[without]] (usually after negative verbs)
#: {{usex|не могу се укључити у расправу, а да не направим неред|t=I cannot enter a discussion without making a mess|lang=sh|inline=1}}
#: {{usex|одлази, а да није рекао ни збогом|t=he's leaving without even saying goodbye|lang=sh|inline=1}}
# ({{term|sc=Cyrl||а|lang=sh}} {{m|sh|sc=Cyrl|и̏па̄к}}) [[and]] [[yet]]
#: {{usex|прави пријатељ зна све о теби, а ипак те воли|t=the real friend knows everything about you, and yet he loves you|lang=sh|inline=1}}
# ({{term|sc=Cyrl||а|lang=sh}} {{m|sh|sc=Cyrl|ка̏моли}}) not to mention, [[let alone]]
#: {{usex|у мору лоших в(иј)ести тешко је остати објективан, а камоли оптимистичан|t=in the sea of bad news it's hard to stay objective, let alone optimistic|lang=sh|inline=1}}
# ({{term|sc=Cyrl||а|lang=sh}} + {{term|sc=Cyrl|и|lang=sh}} + {{term|sc=Cyrl|да|lang=sh}}) [[even if]]
#: {{usex|а и да јесам то направио, не би то учинило неку разлику|t=even if I did it, it wouldn't have made much of a difference|lang=sh|inline=1}}
# ({{term|sc=Cyrl||а|lang=sh}} + {{term|sc=Cyrl|и|lang=sh}}) and [[so]], and [[also]], and [[too]]
#: {{usex|свиђају ми се плавуше, а и ја се покојој свидим|t=I like blondes, and some of them even like me|lang=sh|inline=1}}
#: {{usex|били су жалосни, а и ја сам|t=they were sad, and so am I|lang=sh|inline=1}}

===Etymology 3===
Attested since the 15th century. Probably of onomatopoeic origin. Compare Slovene {{term|a|lang=sl}}, Russian {{term|а|lang=ru}}, Lithuanian {{m|lt|õ}}, Latin {{m|la|ō}} and Ancient Greek {{term|ὦ|lang=grc}}. These could all derive from Proto-Indo-European interjection {{m|ine-pro||ō|oh, ah}}, but each form in individual languages could easily be an independent, expressive formation.

====Interjection====
{{sh-interjection|c|a}}

# [[oh]], [[ah]]
#: {{usex|а да?|t=oh really?|lang=sh|inline=1}}

